text: You man babies (and yes some of you women too) literally hate Brie for absolutely no fucking reason, it‚Äôs irrational. Y‚Äôall know Brie doesn‚Äôt hate white dudes right? Basically if you‚Äôre familiar with the movie ‚ÄúA Wrinkle In Time‚Äù it didn‚Äôt do as well most of the negative reviews were by white male critics. Brie had made a statement basically saying she didn‚Äôt want to hear what some old white dude thought about the movie because it dealt more with a connection to women of color and biracial women and Brie felt they should have a better opportunity to review and criticize the movie as it hits home to them. And it‚Äôs true, a majority of critics are about 79% men and most are white and about 21% women and it‚Äôs not at all racist to call someone by what race they are...js. As for her comments about the Captain Marvel movie Brie had said she wanted there to be more diversity and seats at the table (in reference to non white men and also women), however she went on to say in that statement she wanted no seats taken away (in reference to white men). When the first Captain Marvel trailer came out a bunch of trolls kept telling her to ‚Äúsmile more‚Äù and Brie clapped back to that by photoshopping smiles on Marvel male leads as a clap back around the time the official trailer for Captain Marvel came out. I mean seriously though what is it with some guys and telling women to smile all the time? I mean I don‚Äôt see y‚Äôall asking the male leads to smile more...js. ü§∑üèæ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è And don‚Äôt say ‚Äúcause she acts like she acts with no emotion‚Äù because literally the character of CM lost her memory and they said various times in the movie Carol Danvers struggled with her emotions so actually Brie played the character just right! After Brie clapped back with putting smiles on the male leads triggered trolls saw Bries statements on the Wrinkle in Time Movie as an opportunity to ruin her image and twisted her words out of context to spread the false idea that Brie hates men or more specifically white men and didn‚Äôt want them to see Captain Marvel which clearly is very much FALSE.   Regardless it doesn‚Äôt make sense for her to hate white men or men in general because she has a white father, has white male friends and family, she used to be engaged to a man who guess what? He is white! Not to mention she is currently dating a white man and works with women, white men and or men in general and not to mention she is white so that whole she‚Äôs ‚Äúracist‚Äù and ‚Äúsexist‚Äù towards white men or any man in general is absurd and ridiculous. She‚Äôs an introvert and is very sarcastic as a way of joking around or breaking the ice in conversation (which I understand cause I‚Äôm the same way) but y‚Äôall mistake it for her being ‚Äúcocky‚Äù or ‚Äúbitchy‚Äù and having ‚Äúhorrible personality‚Äù (Which I don‚Äôt get cause when guys are like that they‚Äôre seen as badass, laid back or mysterious...hypocritical and ironic if you ask me).  Y‚Äôall hate her personal views even though RDJ holds a lot of the same views just like almost pretty much the entire cast of the Avengers and yet y‚Äôall aren‚Äôt spouting hate at them. I mean where was your hate when Scarlett Johanson spoke at the women‚Äôs march on behalf of women being treated unfairly and constantly being sexually assaulted back in 2018?...I mean since y‚Äôall hate feminists so much. Where was your hate when RDJ said he was in full support of Iron Heart appearing in the MCU? I mean since y‚Äôall flip about female leads getting equal spotlight as the male leads. I mean like I said they share the same views as Brie and y‚Äôall like to say you don‚Äôt agree with Bries views as a reason to hate her but again I don‚Äôt see y‚Äôall hating on everyone else and don‚Äôt try to say ‚Äúwell she acts like a cocky know it all‚Äù as an excuse even though it‚Äôs not true not to mention RDJ and Chris H. act like cocky, sarcastic, know it alls in their interviews all the time and y‚Äôall don‚Äôt hate on them. (I love and admire Chris Hemsworth and RDJ but I‚Äôm just pointing out the double standards and bs y‚Äôall hold against Brie).   There was already a lot of pressure on Brie from the moment the first CM trailer came because Marvel was finally debuting their first female lead superhero film and y‚Äôall clearly like the women to stay in the back and let the male leads shine (figuratively speaking) I mean y‚Äôall lost your shit when the women teamed up in Endgame saying it was ‚Äúforced‚Äù although it‚Äôs the exact same thing shown as with the male leads but just with women. Tbh idk what is it about Brie that y‚Äôall find so bothering but she literally gets along with everyone and anyone that has worked with her in the movies always had something positive to say about her. Not to mention yes she does get along with Chris H. they just joke around and being sarcastic with each other most of the time on who‚Äôs stronger but that‚Äôs all it is joking around and sarcasm and y‚Äôall think she hates him and make YouTube videos about it even though it‚Äôs false, even Don Cheadle (War machine) spoke out against you trolls on behalf on Brie not hating on Chris and called out you triggered trolls on Twitter for it for making negative shit up about Brie.   Still don‚Äôt like her? Oh well too bad get the fuck over yourselves cause clearly she aint bothered about y‚Äôall. I thought I shed some light on the ACTUAL FACTS over this whole hating on Brie nonsense. Say whatever negative comment you want on this I really don‚Äôt care cause it‚Äôs just bs. Get over yourselves.

text: I‚Äôm from the town this entire incident took place. One of my grandparents found Ms Morrison‚Äôs body that day. I was 13 when it happened. Went to school with his daughter actually. I know the Monroeville Police Department ‚Äúdetectives‚Äù that mangled the crime scene up horribly. One just retired and the other is still an investigator for the DA here. I knew the DA at the time, who‚Äôs since passed away. Now I also knew several of the County Sheriff Deputy‚Äôs at the time and the ABI investigator. Funny thing is, ONLY the MPD people thought Mr McMillian was guilty. Seriously. They bungled the crime scene and destroyed it just trying to be big shots and make a name for themselves. The ABI guy was a black man and I never got to ask him his thoughts, later when I was older and better prepared to dig into this for a term paper. He was out of the area on medical or family emergency. The Sheriff‚Äôs department was made to stand down and stay away because they knew he was getting railroaded. They weren‚Äôt allowed access to the investigation so they couldn‚Äôt prove it at the time. One of the lead detectives for MCSO was a classmate‚Äôs dad and had a decade plus on the force and because he was raising so much hell about them convicting the wrong man, prior during and after the trial, a couple of attempts on his life were made. Seriously. He was forced to step down and take a job on the Reservation Police Force about 30 minutes south of here. He only shut up when both of his daughters‚Äô lives were threatened. Then he basically just worked low key to try to help prove the State wrong.  I will also say this. For the most part, the area this happened in is very NOT racist. Hell, we were/are all too poor to be racists honestly. And that‚Äôs true of most of the South. Unfortunately, the dumb ass pieces of trash that are too ignorant to tie their shoes that are racists become more of the headlines. I went to school with several of Mr McMillian‚Äôs kids and relatives. They are some of the best people you will ever hope to meet in your life. That entire family are very humble, good hearted, extremely loving people. They‚Äôd give you the shirt off their backs and honestly didn‚Äôt have a shirt to spare. But that‚Äôs how good they are. And they are big time in the church and great Christians, if that matters to you. I know some people use religion as a crutch but this family does not. They are not hypocrites at all. Mrs McMillian has given me hugs and bandaged my booboos when I‚Äôd have a bike wreck over there playing with the other boys in the area. And too, she‚Äôs put a switch or flip flop to my ass as well. If you were in her yard playing, then you were her family and were treated like such, good or bad behavior on your part. Mr McMillian I didn‚Äôt know much because he was always working to provide for his family. I cried with one of his nieces the day he was convicted. And I cried with her and her kids when he was cleared and released. I just can‚Äôt tell or express how good these people are. And how disgustingly mean and wrong they were treated. And I hope people don‚Äôt think that all us white people in the south are the racists bigots and scum that people portray us as or think of us as. I can‚Äôt swear that‚Äôs not the case, because y‚Äôall don‚Äôt know me so it wouldn‚Äôt matter. But I hope you can actually look around and see that truthfully the dirtbags that are racists and do treat people bad, are a very small minority. Hope this movie is as good as it should be, and I love that Jamie Fox and Michael B. Jordan are playing the key roles. That alone means there‚Äôs lots of heart and love in the story. IMO. Peace and love to you all. And just love your fellow mankind. There‚Äôs no reason, justification or really energy you should waste on people that treat you bad, and a single small group shouldn‚Äôt taint your views of an entire group of people regardless of the demographic. The good shall always prevail and the bad will forever fail, no matter your race, gender, political views or sexual orientation.

text: Thought provoking, and emotionally powerful movie about social injustice, innocent people being wrongfully accused, convicted, and executed. It's hard to watch the beginning but even harder to watch the middle without crying. One of the characters, a veteran with PTSD, is on death row  instead of getting the much needed help for his traumatic experience from war which led to his mental illness/breakdown. This was something Jordan's character conveys how the system should help people like him and not brutally tear them down, brush them off from society, or especially execute them.   Michael B. Jordan should receive an award for his acclaimed performance. This was based on a true story from the 2014 memoir turned screenplay. Very hard to see how many people in power could hurt innocent human beings just for basing their hatred on their race, creed, background, or being poor. To think this took place in 1986 -1993 in the town where such a mind blowing book/movie, "To Kill A Mockingbird" was created.   Maybe it's the Catholic in me but I have always thought it's wrong to think and especially act upon the thought of being a judge/jury by taking any living human or living thing's life. I don't believe in euthanizing especially innocent human beings or animals; that is God's timing when one's life ends not ours.  I highly recommend reading the book. So grateful to see there are very few courageous people willing to fight for others til the  end; no matter what roadblocks, anger, hatred, one faces.  Loved some of the eye opening quotes: "We can make this world a better place."  "We all need grace. We all need Mercy. "  "We are willing to stand up when people are telling us to sit down. " (Mr. Bryan Stevenson)  It's courageous that this young Harvard lawyer had so much passion, love, intelligence, integrity, and willingness to fight for those who lost hope. Loved at the end of the film.  I believe in treating people with the respect, love, care, and especially dignity we should give to others. Always fight for those who have lost hope by giving voice to the voiceless. Very good movie to start dialogue on helping the innocent and those forgotten by society due to past mistakes.   "Each of us is more than the worst thing we've ever done. " Love that quote because it's just so powerful in a soul searching, contemplating way. I believe it means despite the worst mistake(s) one has done in life; it shouldn't define you as a person, as a human being God intended you to be when he made you out of love. As human beings, we all aren't perfect and make mistakes we aren't proud of. That's why we are human. If one owns up to those mistakes with humility, remorse, and genuine compassion to rewrite the wrongs; that person is reborn into what we were meant to be, a good hearted person. Mr. Stevenson was right to say one's life is still valued. Life is still meaningful.  "You're life is still meaningful. " (B. Stevenson)

text: A heart wrenching account of injustice at it's very worst at a time when I was visiting the State of Alabama on business from the UK, oblivious to the depth of racism that existed at such a high level. Only now, after watching this film do I realise this was not ignorance, but an institutionalised culture of racism kept alive from a sickening past. It turns out I was the ignorant one. I fail to accept that those who were openly promoting racism at that time have changed in nature - shame on y'all.
